## How to read this

- **X-axis (Differentiation)** answers: *would a competitor with the same
  capability beat us?* High differentiation means our model is hard to copy.
- **Y-axis (Strategic Importance)** answers: *does the business depend on this
  to win?* High importance means losing this BC threatens revenue or
  positioning.
- **Quadrant-1 (top-right) = Core.** Highest leverage. Build in-house, staff
  with senior engineers, accept slow iteration if it preserves the model.
- **Quadrant-3 (bottom-left) = Generic.** Buy or rent. Spending senior time
  here is portfolio mismanagement.
- **Quadrant-2 (top-left) = Strategic Supporting.** Important to win but
  not differentiating — the canonical example is regulatory compliance.
  Build to standard, do not over-invest.
- **Quadrant-4 (bottom-right) = Differentiator at risk.** A capability the
  team thinks is special, but the business doesn't actually depend on it.
  Re-classify or de-fund.

